    {
      "id": "facb82d5f5a41e06ec549df9224aec659d6a28a2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 377,
        "name": "wc-checkpatch",
        "username": "hpdd-checkpatch",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2018-05-16 03:48:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLooks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e57324bcac97a70e28bc39677e28444bc20e6712",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 750,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshanx@google.com",
        "username": "jxiong"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-16 03:55:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Oleg, you suggested to do lock match for direct IO. It turned out that it has huge performance impact. So this patch just disables lock match for direct I/O. Probably we should make an agreement on this before moving forward.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "08860c8bf265c0a9147499ccd0f657b7205ccd1a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 549,
        "name": "Misc Code Checks Robot (Gatekeeper helper)",
        "username": "smatchreview",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2018-05-16 04:00:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nCode-wise looks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0d0e033eddbed941a5e3c976539b25675e6ad547",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-05-16 04:07:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified-1\n\nBuild Failed \n\nhttps://build.hpdd.intel.com/job/lustre-reviews/56513/ : FAILURE",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "942c8dbe8b8a61d09a66b2df7df922cd9f3f6128",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-17 16:12:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(2 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "38e3848fa258ac5d80895a2acc110932c31e65b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 750,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshanx@google.com",
        "username": "jxiong"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-17 18:25:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> (2 comments)\n\nI would like to get Oleg's confirmation before I continue the work, because the patch was blocked because he wanted lock match for direct IO.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "cfbedf712ea0f5921e20110292c2efb98721ada3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-05-29 15:59:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nMy memory of this patch was that we still ended up requesting a read lock to check the size when reading, so this only really worked for writes.  But it seems sound for writes.\n\nCan you be more specific about performance impact?  When does it have a huge impact/how does it show up?  (I will +1 without that, but it would be nice to know :) )\n\nWhy is it a \"temporary patch\", though?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "117e886069e2cbcb790a3472dd37241d67d6a61a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 750,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshanx@google.com",
        "username": "jxiong"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-31 18:20:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> My memory of this patch was that we still ended up requesting a\n > read lock to check the size when reading, so this only really\n > worked for writes.  But it seems sound for writes.\n > \n > Can you be more specific about performance impact?  When does it\n > have a huge impact/how does it show up?  (I will +1 without that,\n > but it would be nice to know :) )\n > \n > Why is it a \"temporary patch\", though?\n\nthis patch will be merged into the 1st patch in the patch set. This patch is to show what changes will be applied because oleg would like to match existing locks for direct IO.\n\nThe overhead is that it has to create cl_lock structure for each I/O. The overhead is significant when doing small like 4KB I/O. Without this patch, I couldn't see any performance improvement in my VM benchmark.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d624cc3a41f870a8f4aa0c6a50765af4ef04cfb6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-18 00:12:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIMHO, doing lockless IO is the best way to move forward for handling small random IO from multiple clients.  Essentially, if the OSTs detect lock contention from multiple nodes and the IO size is small, they stop giving out locks and the clients just dump the pages without caching to the OSS.  We don't want to _always_ do lockless IO (e.g. single client random write, or random read of a \"small\" file), because clients can aggregate multiple writes, and for reads they could do large read IOs into client cache (i.e. LU-11416).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c2dbd120827768bf9a7bca90e5939bb42aeecd50",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 750,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshanx@google.com",
        "username": "jxiong"
      },
      "date": "2019-01-26 19:31:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> IMHO, doing lockless IO is the best way to move forward for\n > handling small random IO from multiple clients.  Essentially, if\n > the OSTs detect lock contention from multiple nodes and the IO size\n > is small, they stop giving out locks and the clients just dump the\n > pages without caching to the OSS.  We don't want to _always_ do\n > lockless IO (e.g. single client random write, or random read of a\n > \"small\" file), because clients can aggregate multiple writes, and\n > for reads they could do large read IOs into client cache (i.e.\n > LU-11416).\n\nYes, I agree with the cases for small I/O.\n\nHowever, the goal of this patch is to handle direct IO mainly. In that case, there is no client cache at all. Also we would expect that the size of direct I/O should be large in general.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
